<dl id="n32057a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n32" href="#n32057a">N32 (VI.B.23)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n32all.htm#n32057a"> 57(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> chaste India</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Not only has Urdu adopted a Persian vocabulary, but even a few peculiarities of Persian construction, such as reversing the position of the governing and the governed word (<i>e.g. bap mera</i> for <i>mera bap</i>), or of the adjective and the substantive it qualifies, or such as the use of Persian phrases with the preposition <i>ba</i> instead of the native postposition of the ablative case &hellip;; and these <font color="green">[practices]</font>, perhaps, combined with the too free indulgence on the part of some authors in the use of high-flown and pedantic Persian and Arabic words in place of common and yet <mark>chaste Indian</mark> words &hellip; have induced some to regard Hindostani or Urdu as a language distinct from Hindi. <small> &ldquo;HINDOSTANI&rdquo; <a name="EBHI" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBHI"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 480(a) [Hindostani as a Lingua Franca]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
